Articles.Content:
United Launch Alliance is launching another Atlas V rocket early Wednesday morning from Cape Canaveral. It's a US Airforce payload adding another satellite to their AEHF satellite constellation, a next-gen secure global communications network.

It's the 40th Atlas V launch. And its at night, so it should look pretty awesome.

More mission details here:http://www.ulalaunch.com/site/pages/Launch.shtml#/43/

Livestream will be here, starting 2:45AM EDT (1 hour, 30 minutes from this posting.

Here's an live channel for launch site updates: http://www.floridatoday.com/livestream/article/99999999/SPACE/130917025/?sf17339490=1

Within the last hour the pad team investigated a faulty sensor on a tank valve. And the range is current No-Go for launch due to Cumulus clouds.
Live stream is up. But the launch is expected to be delayed for up to an hour while the weather clears
After the weather delays, the new T-0 launch time is 4:10 EDT (Roughly 14 minutes)

Launch seems to have been flawless, and its completing its upper stage burn.

Sleep time. Cygnus's 1st trip to the ISS is launching around 9AM EDT
